1. OVERVIEW
===========
P.A.N.D.A. (Procedural Anomaly Narrative Dialogue Architecture) is a modular interactive
conversation system for S.T.A.L.K.E.R. Anomaly. Conversations are delivered as PDA text
messages — think of them as long-distance radio/text exchanges between the player and NPCs
who are physically present somewhere in the game world.

ALL conversations happen over PDA text. The NPC is not standing in front of the player.
They are messaging from wherever they are in the Zone. Write accordingly — no physical
actions ("hands you a package"), no visual descriptions ("looks nervous"). Text messages only.

Each faction has its own XML file containing conversations for players of that faction:
  - st_PANDA_loner_interactive_conversations.xml  (this file — for loner players)
  - st_PANDA_duty_interactive_conversations.xml   (for duty players — future)
  - st_PANDA_freedom_interactive_conversations.xml (for freedom players — future)
  - etc.

The system is fully precondition-driven. There are no separate "friendly" or "hostile"
conversation types. Every conversation defines its own preconditions that control exactly
which NPC can trigger it and under what circumstances. This means:
  - A conversation with "req_npc_friendly:stalker" will only trigger with a friendly loner NPC.
  - A conversation with "req_npc_hostile:bandit" will only trigger with a hostile bandit NPC.
  - Faction relations are checked via GOODWILL, which changes dynamically during gameplay.
  - If the player starts friendly with Duty but relations deteriorate, conversations requiring
    "req_npc_friendly:dolg" will stop triggering — and "req_npc_hostile:dolg" ones will start.

This creates a living, reactive conversation system where the same faction can be friend or foe
depending on the player's actions.


2. HOW THE SYSTEM WORKS
========================
When a conversation triggers, the system does the following:

  1. Finds all eligible NPCs in the game world (alive, not in combat, not on cooldown,
     minimum distance from player, not a trader/zombified/monolith).

  2. Scans through ALL conversations in the player's faction XML file (this file).
     Conversations are numbered sequentially: 1, 2, 3, etc.

  3. For each NPC candidate, checks every conversation's preconditions against that NPC.
     ALL preconditions must pass for a conversation to be eligible (AND logic).

  4. From all eligible conversation+NPC pairs, picks one at random (weighted by cooldown).

  5. Sends the opening message to the player's PDA and presents response choices.

This means the preconditions are the ONLY thing controlling who sends what. You have fine-grained
control over exactly which NPCs can trigger each conversation and under what gameplay conditions.


3. XML KEY FORMAT (CONVERSATION STRUCTURE)
==========================================
Every conversation is a set of XML string entries with a specific naming convention.
The base format is:

    st_pda_ic_<faction>_<id>_<suffix>

Where:
  - <faction> = player's faction (e.g., "loner", "dolg", "freedom", "bandit")
  - <id>      = sequential conversation number (1, 2, 3, ...)
  - <suffix>  = the component type (see below)

REQUIRED COMPONENTS (every conversation needs these):
  _precond    = Comma-separated precondition list (controls who/when this triggers)
  _open       = Opening message from the NPC (first thing the player sees)
  _choice_1   = Player's first response option (minimum 1, maximum 4)
  _reply_1    = NPC's reply to choice 1
  _outcome_1  = Outcome commands for choice 1 (use "none" for no outcome)

OPTIONAL COMPONENTS:
  _choice_2 through _choice_4  = Additional player response options (up to 4 total)
  _reply_2 through _reply_4    = NPC replies for each additional choice
  _outcome_2 through _outcome_4 = Outcomes for each additional choice
  _cont_1 through _cont_4      = Next turn ID to continue the conversation (for branching)
  _timeout                      = Custom timeout in seconds (default: random 90-300)
  _timeout_msg                  = Custom annoyed message when player ignores NPC

EXAMPLE (Conversation 1 for Loner faction):

    st_pda_ic_loner_1_precond       = "req_npc_friendly:stalker,req_npc_rank:experienced"
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_open          = "Hey $player_name, got a minute?"
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_choice_1      = "What do you need?"
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_reply_1       = "Just checking if you're still breathing."
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_outcome_1     = "none"
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_choice_2      = "Busy. Make it quick."
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_reply_2       = "Forget it then."
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_outcome_2     = "none"


4. PRECONDITIONS REFERENCE
===========================
All preconditions are defined in the _precond string entry, separated by commas.
ALL preconditions must pass for the conversation to trigger (AND logic).
Format: command:param1:param2

--- NPC RELATION (GOODWILL-BASED, DYNAMIC) ---

  req_npc_friendly
    NPC must be friendly/neutral toward the player. Uses goodwill — if faction relations
    change during gameplay, this reflects it dynamically.
    Example: req_npc_friendly
    The NPC's faction goodwill must be non-negative AND the NPC's personal relation must
    not be "enemy."

  req_npc_friendly:<faction>
    Same as above, but NPC must ALSO belong to a specific faction.
    Example: req_npc_friendly:stalker    (friendly loner NPC only)
    Example: req_npc_friendly:dolg       (friendly Duty NPC only)
    Example: req_npc_friendly:freedom    (friendly Freedom NPC only)

  req_npc_hostile
    NPC must be hostile toward the player. Uses goodwill — dynamically reflects
    changing faction relations.
    Example: req_npc_hostile
    The NPC's faction goodwill must be negative AND the NPC's personal relation must
    be "enemy."

  req_npc_hostile:<faction>
    Same as above, but NPC must ALSO belong to a specific faction.
    Example: req_npc_hostile:bandit      (hostile bandit NPC only)
    Example: req_npc_hostile:army        (hostile military NPC only)

    IMPORTANT: Goodwill changes over time based on player actions. A Duty member who
    is friendly today may become hostile tomorrow if the player attacks Duty stalkers
    or allies with their enemies. Your conversations will automatically adapt.

--- NPC FACTION (HARD CHECK, ignores goodwill) ---

  req_npc_faction:<faction>
    NPC must belong to this faction, regardless of relation.
    Example: req_npc_faction:dolg        (any Duty NPC, friendly or hostile)

  req_npc_not_faction:<faction>
    NPC must NOT belong to this faction.
    Example: req_npc_not_faction:bandit   (anyone except bandits)

--- PLAYER FACTION ---

  req_faction:<faction>
    Player must belong to this faction.
    Example: req_faction:stalker

  req_not_faction:<faction>
    Player must NOT belong to this faction.
    Example: req_not_faction:monolith

--- NPC RANK ---

  req_npc_rank:<rank>
    NPC rank must be at LEAST this rank.
    Ranks (lowest to highest): novice, trainee, experienced, professional, veteran,
                                expert, master, legend
    Example: req_npc_rank:veteran        (veteran or higher only)

  req_npc_rank_max:<rank>
    NPC rank must be at MOST this rank.
    Example: req_npc_rank_max:trainee    (trainee or lower — rookies only)

--- PLAYER RANK ---

  req_rank:<rank>
    Player rank must be at least this rank.
    Example: req_rank:experienced

  req_rank_max:<rank>
    Player rank must be at most this rank.
    Example: req_rank_max:novice         (new players only)

--- MONEY ---

  req_money:<amount>
    Player must have at least this many RU.
    Example: req_money:5000

  req_money_max:<amount>
    Player must have LESS than this many RU.
    Example: req_money_max:500           (player is broke)

--- REPUTATION ---

  req_rep:<value>
    Player reputation must be >= this value.
    Example: req_rep:500

  req_rep_max:<value>
    Player reputation must be <= this value.
    Example: req_rep_max:-100            (player has bad reputation)

--- KILLS ---

  req_kills:<count>
    Player must have killed at least this many stalkers.
    Example: req_kills:50

  req_mutant_kills:<count>
    Player must have killed at least this many mutants.
    Example: req_mutant_kills:20

--- FACTION GOODWILL (DIRECT VALUE CHECK) ---

  req_goodwill:<amount>:<faction>
    Player goodwill with a specific faction must be >= amount.
    Example: req_goodwill:500:dolg       (at least 500 goodwill with Duty)

  req_goodwill_max:<amount>:<faction>
    Player goodwill with a specific faction must be <= amount.
    Example: req_goodwill_max:-500:bandit (very hostile with bandits)

--- LOCATION ---

  req_level:<level_name>
    Player must be on this specific map.
    Example: req_level:l03_agroprom

  req_not_level:<level_name>
    Player must NOT be on this map.
    Example: req_not_level:l01_escape

--- COMPANIONS ---

  req_companions:<count>
    Player must have at least this many companions.
    Example: req_companions:1            (player has at least 1 companion)

  req_companions_max:<count>
    Player must have at most this many companions.
    Example: req_companions_max:0        (player is alone)

--- INVENTORY ---

  req_has_item:<section_name>
    Player must have this item in inventory.
    Example: req_has_item:wpn_ak74

  req_equipped:<section_name>
    Player must have this item equipped.
    Example: req_equipped:wpn_svd

  req_equipped_slot:<slot_number>
    Player must have something in this equipment slot.
    Example: req_equipped_slot:2         (has a weapon in slot 2)

--- TIME OF DAY ---

  req_time_day
    Must be daytime (06:00 - 20:00).
    Example: req_time_day

  req_time_night
    Must be nighttime (20:00 - 06:00).
    Example: req_time_night

--- HEALTH ---

  req_health_min:<value>
    Player health must be >= this value (0.0 to 1.0 scale).
    Example: req_health_min:0.5          (at least 50% health)

  req_health_max:<value>
    Player health must be <= this value.
    Example: req_health_max:0.3          (critically wounded)

--- ACHIEVEMENTS ---

  req_achievement:<achievement_name>
    Player must have earned this achievement.
    Example: req_achievement:ach_marked_by_zone

--- COMBINING PRECONDITIONS ---

  All preconditions are combined with AND logic. Comma-separate them:

  Example: "req_npc_friendly:stalker,req_npc_rank:experienced,req_money:5000"
    = Friendly loner NPC, at least experienced rank, player has 5000+ RU

  Example: "req_npc_hostile:bandit,req_npc_rank_max:trainee,req_rank:veteran"
    = Hostile bandit rookie, player is at least veteran rank

  Example: "req_npc_friendly:dolg,req_time_night,req_level:l04_darkvalley"
    = Friendly Duty member, nighttime, player is in Dark Valley

  FACTION NAME LIST:
    stalker (or loner) = Loners         dolg (or duty) = Duty
    freedom = Freedom                   bandit = Bandits
    army (or military) = Military       killer (or mercenary) = Mercenaries
    ecolog (or scientist) = Ecologists  csky (or clear_sky) = Clear Sky
    monolith = Monolith                 renegade = Renegades
    greh = UNISG                        isg = ISG
    zombied (or zombie) = Zombified


5. OUTCOMES REFERENCE
=====================
Outcomes are actions that happen when the player picks a response. Defined in _outcome_N
entries. Use "none" for no outcome. Multiple outcomes are comma-separated.
Format: command:param1:param2

--- MONEY ---

  reward_money:<amount>
    Give player money.
    Example: reward_money:2000           (player receives 2000 RU)

  punish_money:<amount>
    Deduct money from player (capped at what they have).
    Example: punish_money:1000           (player loses 1000 RU)

--- REPUTATION ---

  reward_rep:<amount>
    Increase player reputation.
    Example: reward_rep:50

  punish_rep:<amount>
    Decrease player reputation.
    Example: punish_rep:25

--- FACTION GOODWILL ---

  reward_gw:<amount>:<faction>
    Improve player's goodwill with a faction.
    Example: reward_gw:100:dolg          (improve relations with Duty by 100)

  punish_gw:<amount>:<faction>
    Decrease player's goodwill with a faction.
    Example: punish_gw:50:freedom        (worsen relations with Freedom by 50)

    NOTE: Changing goodwill WILL affect which conversations trigger in the future.
    If you punish_gw enough with a faction, conversations requiring req_npc_friendly
    for that faction will stop triggering and req_npc_hostile ones will start.

--- ITEMS ---

  give_item:<section_name>
    Spawn an item directly into player's inventory.
    Example: give_item:medkit_army

  courier_item:<section_name>
    Spawn a courier NPC who delivers the item to the player.
    Example: courier_item:wpn_ak74

--- SPAWNING ---

  spawn_hostile:<faction>:<distance>
    Spawn a hostile squad near the player.
    Example: spawn_hostile:bandit:90     (spawn bandits ~90m from player)

  spawn_mutant:<type>:<distance>
    Spawn a mutant squad. Type can be "random" or a specific mutant.
    Example: spawn_mutant:random:90      (spawn random mutants ~90m away)
    Example: spawn_mutant:bloodsucker:60

  spawn_companion:<faction>:<distance>
    Spawn a friendly squad that joins the player.
    Example: spawn_companion:stalker:30  (spawn friendly loners ~30m away)

--- STASH ---

  reward_stash
    Reveal a random stash location on the player's map.
    Example: reward_stash

    CRITICAL: The stash location is determined randomly by the game engine at runtime.
    You have NO control over where it will be. NEVER write dialogue that specifies where
    the stash is ("I hid it behind the old water tower"). The player will get map
    coordinates — that is all you know. Write dialogue like: "I'll send you the
    coordinates" or "Marking the location on your PDA."

--- LOCATION MARKERS ---

  watch_location:<smart_terrain_key>
    Add a PDA map marker at a smart terrain and notify the player.
    The smart terrain key must be a real vanilla smart terrain string ID.
    Example: watch_location:st_esc_smart_terrain_4_13_name

  watch_location:<smart_terrain_key>:<radius>
    Same but with custom detection radius (default 85m).
    Example: watch_location:st_gar_smart_terrain_3_5_name:100

  watch_location_trigger:<smart_terrain_key>:<command>:<params>:<radius>
    Place a marker AND trigger an outcome command when the player arrives.
    Example: watch_location_trigger:st_gar_smart_terrain_3_5_name:spawn_hostile:bandit:90:100
    = Mark a location, and when player gets within 100m, spawn hostile bandits.

--- NPC TELEPORTATION ---

  teleport_npc_to_smart:<smart_terrain_key>
    Teleport the conversation NPC to a smart terrain location.
    Example: teleport_npc_to_smart:st_esc_smart_terrain_4_13_name

  teleport_npc_to_smart:<smart_terrain_key>:<delay_seconds>
    Same but with a delay.
    Example: teleport_npc_to_smart:st_gar_smart_terrain_3_5_name:5

  teleport_npc_to_player
    Teleport the conversation NPC near the player.
    Example: teleport_npc_to_player

  teleport_npc_to_player:<delay_seconds>
    Same but with a delay.
    Example: teleport_npc_to_player:10

--- COMPANION RECRUITMENT ---

  recruit_companion
    Convert the conversation NPC into a player companion.
    Example: recruit_companion

  recruit_companion:no_dismiss
    Same but the companion cannot be dismissed.
    Example: recruit_companion:no_dismiss

--- CHANCE MODIFIER ---

  chance:<percent>:<command>
    Roll a percentage chance before executing an outcome.
    Example: chance:50:reward_money:1000     (50% chance to get 1000 RU)
    Example: chance:25:spawn_hostile:bandit:90 (25% chance to spawn bandits)

--- COMBINING OUTCOMES ---

  Comma-separate multiple outcomes:
    Example: "reward_money:2000,reward_rep:25,reward_gw:50:stalker"
    = Give 2000 RU + 25 reputation + 50 loner goodwill


6. DYNAMIC PLACEHOLDERS
========================
Use these in your dialogue text. They are replaced at runtime with real game data.

  $player_name       = Player's character name
  $npc_name          = Conversation NPC's name
  $player_faction    = Player's faction display name (e.g., "Loners")
  $npc_faction       = NPC's faction display name
  $current_level     = Name of the map the player is currently on
  $player_money      = Player's current RU balance
  $player_rank       = Player's rank name (e.g., "veteran")
  $player_reputation = Player's reputation value
  $companion_count   = Number of player's companions
  $time_of_day       = "morning", "afternoon", "evening", or "night"
  $game_hour         = Current time in HH:MM format

  SMART TERRAIN PLACEHOLDERS:
  %<level>_panda_st%   = Resolves to a random real smart terrain name on that level.
                          The same placeholder always resolves to the same location
                          within one conversation (cached per conversation).
    Example: %cordon_panda_st%       might resolve to "Rookie Village" or "Farm"
    Example: %garbage_panda_st%      might resolve to "Flea Market" or "Hangar"
    Example: %darkvalley_panda_st%   might resolve to "Bandit Base"

  Available level keys:
    cordon, darkscape, swamp, garbage, agroprom, darkvalley, yantar,
    wildterritory, rostok, deadcity, truck_cemetery, meadow, radar,
    red_forest, limansk, pripyat, generators, outskirts, jupiter,
    south_cnpp, north_cnpp, zaton


7. SMART TERRAIN LOCATION SYSTEM
=================================
The smart terrain system lets conversations reference REAL vanilla game locations.
This is critical for immersion — every location mentioned in a conversation exists
in the actual game world and uses the game's own name for that place.

HOW IT WORKS:
  - Use %<level>_panda_st% in dialogue text to automatically pick a random
    real location on that map.
  - The system caches the chosen location for the entire conversation, so if you
    reference %cordon_panda_st% multiple times, it always resolves to the same place.
  - You can then use watch_location in an outcome to mark that location on the PDA.

EXAMPLE USAGE IN DIALOGUE:
    "Heard there's good salvage near %garbage_panda_st%. Worth checking out."

    The system resolves this to a real location like "Flea Market" or "Hangar" and
    if you use watch_location in the outcome, it marks that exact spot on the player's map.

RULES:
  - ALWAYS use smart terrain placeholders or real smart terrain IDs for locations.
  - NEVER invent fictional locations. No "the old watchtower," no "behind the fridge
    in the abandoned cabin," no "the dead drop under the bridge." These places do not
    exist in the game. The player cannot go there.
  - NEVER describe specific details about a location's appearance that may not match
    the actual game location. Keep location references vague: "the area," "that spot,"
    "the place I mentioned."
  - If you need to send someone to a location, use watch_location to mark a real
    smart terrain. The game handles the rest.


8. MULTI-TURN CONVERSATIONS
============================
Conversations can branch into multiple turns. Use the _cont_N suffix to specify which
conversation turn follows a player choice.

FORMAT:
  Turn 1 (default):     st_pda_ic_<fac>_<id>_choice_1, _reply_1, _outcome_1, _cont_1
  Turn 2:               st_pda_ic_<fac>_<id>_t2_choice_1, _t2_reply_1, _t2_outcome_1, _t2_cont_1
  Turn 3:               st_pda_ic_<fac>_<id>_t3_choice_1, _t3_reply_1, ...
  etc.

HOW _cont_N WORKS:
  - _cont_1 through _cont_4 specify the next turn number after that choice.
  - If _cont_1 is "2", after the player picks choice 1 and receives reply 1,
    the conversation continues with turn 2 choices.
  - If _cont_N is absent or empty, the conversation ends after that reply.

EXAMPLE (2-turn conversation):
    Turn 1:
      _open       = "Need a hand with something."
      _choice_1   = "What is it?"          _reply_1   = "Quick job, interested?"  _cont_1 = "2"
      _choice_2   = "Not interested."      _reply_2   = "Suit yourself."          (no _cont)

    Turn 2 (only reached via choice 1):
      _t2_choice_1 = "Sure, what's the pay?"   _t2_reply_1 = "2000 RU."   _t2_outcome_1 = "reward_money:2000"
      _t2_choice_2 = "Changed my mind."        _t2_reply_2 = "Your loss."  _t2_outcome_2 = "none"


9. CONVERSATION TIMEOUTS
=========================
If the player ignores a conversation (doesn't pick a response), the NPC will eventually
get annoyed and end the conversation. This prevents conversations from hanging forever.

  _timeout      = Timeout in seconds (real time). Default: random 90-300 seconds.
  _timeout_msg  = Custom annoyed message. If not set, a random generic one is used.

EXAMPLE:
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_timeout     = "60"
    st_pda_ic_loner_1_timeout_msg = "Fine, ignore me. See if I care."


10. WRITING RULES AND GUIDELINES
==================================

--- IMMERSION AND TONE ---

  a) THESE ARE TEXT MESSAGES. All conversations happen over long-distance PDA communication.
     Write like someone texting on a rugged handheld device in a radioactive wasteland.
     - DO: Short sentences. Abbreviations. Slang. Typos are fine for low-rank NPCs.
     - DON'T: Long poetic monologues. Physical descriptions. Actions like *hands you a drink*.

  b) NOT EVERYONE IS FRIENDLY. The Zone is full of desperate, paranoid, aggressive, shady,
     and unhinged people. Vary personalities across conversations:
     - Gruff veterans who don't waste words.
     - Nervous rookies who overshare.
     - Sarcastic traders who only care about profit.
     - Hostile contacts who threaten before negotiating.
     - Paranoid loners who trust nobody.
     - Drunk stalkers rambling at 3 AM.
     Not every NPC should sound like a polite quest-giver. Give them PERSONALITY.

  c) STAY LORE-FRIENDLY. This is S.T.A.L.K.E.R. Anomaly. Reference the Zone, artifacts,
     anomalies, mutants, factions, and real game locations. Don't invent lore that
     contradicts the established universe.

  d) USE REAL DATA. Every piece of information in a conversation should come from real
     gameplay data via placeholders ($player_name, $npc_faction, %cordon_panda_st%, etc.)
     or be vague enough that it could apply to any situation.

--- LOCATIONS ---

  e) NEVER reference fictional locations. No "the old cabin by the creek," no "behind
     the fridge in watchtower 7," no "the dead drop in the sewer." If it doesn't exist
     as a smart terrain in the game, don't mention it.

  f) For location-based conversations, use %<level>_panda_st% placeholders. These resolve
     to real vanilla smart terrain names that actually exist in the game world.

  g) When writing about stashes: the system randomly assigns stash locations at runtime.
     You do NOT know where a stash will be. NEVER describe the stash location in dialogue.
     Write: "I'll send coordinates to your PDA" — NOT: "It's behind the rock near the bridge."

--- OUTCOMES ---

  h) Some outcomes are OUTSIDE your control as a writer. The system handles the specifics:
     - reward_stash: You don't know where the stash will spawn. Don't describe its location.
     - spawn_hostile/spawn_mutant: You don't know exact spawn position. Don't say "from the north."
     - spawn_companion: The NPC spawns near the player. Don't specify where they come from.
     - courier_item: A courier NPC is spawned and walks to the player. Don't describe the courier.
     Write dialogue that references the CONCEPT ("I'll send someone with supplies") not the
     SPECIFICS ("A guy in a brown jacket will meet you at the train tracks").

  i) Match outcomes to dialogue context. If the NPC says "Here's some cash for your trouble,"
     the outcome should include reward_money. If the NPC threatens to send trouble,
     use spawn_hostile. Don't disconnect dialogue from outcomes.

--- PRECONDITIONS AND CONTEXT ---

  j) Every conversation MUST have a _precond entry. At minimum, use req_npc_friendly or
     req_npc_hostile to control whether friendly or hostile NPCs trigger it. Without this,
     any NPC could trigger any conversation, breaking immersion.

  k) USE PRECONDITIONS FOR CONTEXT. If a conversation is about being a veteran, use
     req_npc_rank:veteran. If it's about the player being broke, use req_money_max:500.
     The preconditions create the context that makes the dialogue believable.

  l) Write dialogue that MATCHES the preconditions. If you require req_npc_rank:veteran,
     don't write dialogue where the NPC sounds like a clueless rookie. If you require
     req_npc_hostile, don't write dialogue where the NPC is offering friendly help.

  m) Use req_npc_friendly or req_npc_hostile with a faction parameter for conversations
     specific to a particular faction's personality. Duty members speak differently than
     Freedom members. Bandits speak differently than ecologists.

--- GENERAL CRAFT ---

  n) Keep conversations concise. This is a PDA text exchange, not a novel. Most messages
     should be 1-3 sentences. Long walls of text break immersion.

  o) Give meaningful choices. Don't offer 4 choices that all lead to the same outcome.
     Choices should feel like they matter — different tones, different outcomes, different
     consequences.

  p) Use multi-turn conversations sparingly. Most exchanges should be 1-2 turns.
     A 5-turn conversation over PDA text feels unrealistic.

  q) Test your precondition combinations. If you require req_npc_friendly:bandit for a
     loner player, that conversation will almost never trigger because loners are rarely
     friendly with bandits. Make sure your preconditions create realistic scenarios.


11. COMMON MISTAKES TO AVOID
==============================
  X  Using _friendly_ or _hostile_ in conversation IDs.
     The old system is deprecated. Use st_pda_ic_loner_1_*, NOT st_pda_ic_friendly_loner_1_*.
     Control friendly/hostile via preconditions instead.

  X  Writing fictional locations.
     "Meet me at the old windmill." — There is no old windmill. Use smart terrain placeholders.

  X  Describing stash locations in dialogue.
     "I left it under the stairs." — You don't know where the stash will spawn. Write vaguely.

  X  Physical actions in text messages.
     "*slides a medkit across the table*" — This is a PDA text conversation. They're not
     physically there.

  X  Every NPC sounding the same.
     If every conversation reads like a polite, helpful assistant, you're doing it wrong.
     Zone stalkers are rough, diverse, and unpredictable.

  X  Missing preconditions.
     A conversation without preconditions can trigger with any NPC. A hostile bandit
     shouldn't be offering to share campfire stories.

  X  Hardcoding NPC names.
     Use $npc_name placeholder instead. The system picks a real NPC from the game world.

  X  Not testing precondition feasibility.
     "req_npc_friendly:monolith" for a loner player — Monolith is almost always hostile
     to everyone. This conversation will never trigger.


12. FULL EXAMPLE CONVERSATIONS
================================

EXAMPLE 1: Friendly loner veteran offers a stash tip
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Preconditions: req_npc_friendly:stalker,req_npc_rank:veteran
  (A friendly loner NPC who is at least veteran rank)

  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_precond">
      <text>req_npc_friendly:stalker,req_npc_rank:veteran</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_open">
      <text>$player_name. Still kicking? Got some coordinates I don't need anymore. Interested?</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_choice_1">
      <text>Sure, send them over.</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_reply_1">
      <text>Sending now. Don't expect anything fancy. Good luck out there.</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_outcome_1">
      <text>reward_stash</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_choice_2">
      <text>What's the catch?</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_reply_2">
      <text>No catch. Heading south, won't need them. Take it or leave it.</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_outcome_2">
      <text>reward_stash</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_choice_3">
      <text>Not interested.</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_reply_3">
      <text>Your loss.</text>
  </string>
  <string id="st_pda_ic_loner_1_outcome_3">
